%I A394432 #23 Mar 27 2026 12:01:02
%S A394432 1,5,11,7,11,11,11,23,17,13,17,19,17,19,47,23,29,23,23,23,25,43,31,47,
%T A394432 29,29,41,41,41,29,29,43,31,37,59,29,47,29,47,47,31,31,31,47,43,41,41,
%U A394432 67,37,53,37,41,37,37,37,37,41,37,41,37,43,41,83,41,47,41,61
%N A394432 a(n) is the least r such that ord(n,r) >= (log_2(n))^2, where ord(n,r) is the multiplicative order of n modulo r.
%C A394432 a(n) is the value of r given in the second step of the AKS primality test.
%C A394432 Conjecture: a(n) is always an odd prime power. It seems that most terms are of the form p^k for odd prime p and k <= 3. Other than a(110) = a(119) = 81 and a(n) = 625 for n = 3961388, 4132533, 4466762, 4610283, 4629398, 4961877, 4966163, 5006623, 5054222, 5063527, 5276203, 5314622, 5338663, is there any other term that is a prime power with exponent higher than 3?
%C A394432 Conjecture: for n > 2 being a power of 2, there is no difference between ">= (log_2(n))^2" and "> (log_2(n))^2"; in other words, we actually have ord(2^e,a(2^e)) = ord(2,a(2^e))/gcd(ord(2,a(2^e)), e) > e^2 for e > 1.
%C A394432 Smallest n such that a(n) = 5^3, 7^3, 11^3, 13^3, 17^3: 583, 54787, 5419620025, <=13336632882761, <=226263538686523670939.
%H A394432 Jianing Song, <a href="/A394432/b394432.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 2..10000</a>
%H A394432 Jianing Song, <a href="/A394432/a394432.txt">Further notes on A394432</a>
%H A394432 Wikipedia, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AKS_primality_test">AKS primality test</a>
%e A394432 a(9) = 23: we have (log_2(9))^2 = 10.04842..., and so ord(9,23) = 11 > (log_2(9)). For r < 23, either r is not coprime to 9 or ord(9,r) <= 10 < (log_2(9)).
%o A394432 (PARI) a(n) = my(bound=ceil((log(n)/log(2))^2)); for(m=bound, oo, if(gcd(m,n)==1 && znorder(Mod(n,m))>=bound, return(m)))
%K A394432 nonn
%O A394432 2,2
%A A394432 _Jianing Song_, Mar 20 2026
